I (Thome et al. 1998). PEEP increases were most usually associated with a fall in tidal compliance suggesting overdistension (Dinger et al. 2001; Alegria et al. 2006). Infants with more severe lung disease may, however, demonstrate an improvement in compliance with PEEP increments indicating lung recruitment (Dinger et al. 2001). The level of applied PEEP also has the potential to impact upon cardiac function, but it is clear that the adverse effects of PEEP on cardiac output are much more prominent in the normal lung (Holzman and Scarpelli 1979). This relates to the transmission of intra-alveolar pressure to the pleural and mediastinal compartment, which is substantially greater in a recruited lung. Indeed, one study in the pre-surfactant era used rise in pleural pressure (as indicated by oesophageal pressure) to indicate the point at which lung recruitment had occurred during PEEP increments (Bonta et al. 1977).
